stylometry: The main factor when determining when to place an order and how often is to take into consideration the fixed costs of production and ordering costs.  There is usually an added order cost on top of the cost of the inventory so the company wants to make as few orders during the year as possible without ordering too much inventory but they also want to order enough so that they can satisfy the demand of the product. Revenue, holding costs, set-up costs, production costs, order costs, and the demand are all factors that need to be considered when trying to place an order. Also, businesses that produce perishable items need to take that into account when determining when to order because they can wind up losing money. Another factor would be the price of the inventory throughout the year.  Grocery stores take into consideration when certain produce are in season. For example, during the winter months citrus fruits such as clementines and grapefruit are in abundance in the grocery store and they are much cheaper than other times of the year.  There is so much available so the price to purchase is low and they do not perish as fast as some other produce so grocery stores take this into consideration when ordering from farms.
